{
  "query": "What are the general effects on biodiversity of creating linear depressions or elevations on intertidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across studies of linear depressions (grooves) and elevations (ridges/ledges) on intertidal artificial structures, community and population responses were mixed: groove habitats sometimes altered community composition or supported species absent from flat surfaces, while other studies found no change [3473, 3474]. Species richness/diversity frequently increased with grooves and small ridges/ledges (often alongside pits/other features), but several studies reported no increase or mixed effects depending on size/arrangement, shore level, site, or presence of additional features [3473, 3474]. Comparisons within structured designs reported that grooves often supported higher species richness than adjacent small ridges/ledges, though diversity patterns could depend on feature depth/height [3473, 3464]. For large ridges/ledges, diversity and overall abundance increased in some cases (often with grooves/small protrusions), but other studies reported no increase in richness; certain invertebrates (e.g., mussels or limpets) increased while barnacles did not, and rockweed increased in one study [3465]. Abundance responses for macroalgae and invertebrates to grooves and small ridges/ledges were also variable, with increases in some studies and no or mixed effects in others, including taxon-specific outcomes such as higher oyster or mobile invertebrate abundances in grooves relative to small ledges in some comparisons [3473, 3474, 3464]. Fish responses were generally limited, with fish richness and abundance often unchanged by grooves and small ridges/ledges, though some studies recorded increased richness/abundance or behavioral changes (e.g., more feeding activity) in treatments that included grooves and/or large ledges [3473, 3474, 3465].",
